Wednesday, February 6, 2013







The "Fiscal Cliff" Legislation: Key Provisions for Individuals







In December 2012, the president signed the “Fiscal Cliff” legislation into law, after being passed by the Senate and House of Representatives .  Even though the final resolutions of issues related to spending cuts and the debt ceiling were put off, the legislation did address and resolve most of the tax uncertainty that made year-end planning for 2012 so difficult.



The following are key provisions for individuals in the legislation:


1. Extension of the Bush-era tax cuts for those with taxable income below $450,000 (joint) or $400,000 (single). Taxable income above these levels will be subject to an income tax rate of 39.6%, up from the 2012 rate of 35%.


2. The income tax rate on long-term capital gains and qualified dividends remains at 15% for those with taxable income below $450,000 (joint) or $400,000 (single).  For those with income above these amounts, a rate of 20% will apply to long-term capital gains and qualified dividends.


3. Itemized deductions will be reduced by 3% of the excess of Adjusted Gross Income (AGI) over $300,000 (joint) or $250,000 (single). However, itemized deductions can’t be reduced by more than 80%.


4. Personal exemptions will also be reduced for those with AGI in excess of $300,000 (joint) and $250,000 (single). The reduction is 2% for each $2,500 of AGI in excess of these threshold amounts. This means that exemptions are reduced to zero if AGI exceeds $425,000 (joint) or $375,000 (single).


5. The employee portion of the Social Security withholding tax increases from 4.2% to 6.2%. This increase also applies to those subject to the self-employment tax.


6. The estate tax exemption remains at $5 million. However the top estate tax rate increases from 35% to 40%.


7. The AMT exemption was increased to 2012 “patch” levels and the change was made permanent. 



In addition, the legislation includes permanent extensions to both the adoption and dependent care credits. Certain deductions were given two-year extensions including: the $250 deduction for teachers’ classroom expenses, the state sales tax deduction (in lieu of deducting state income taxes) and charitable donations of assets in an IRA account.



The legislation did not affect the Medicare tax surcharge on earned income or the 3.8% net investment income tax that applied to those with modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) in excess of $250,000 (joint) or $200,000 (single).  These taxes were added by the Affordable Health Care Act and apply beginning of 2013.





