Friday, April 8, 2011










How Long to Keep Those Documents?This is the time of year when we all start thinking about income taxes. As you wade through your piles of receipts and various statements, you may question which documents need to be saved and for how long. Although there is no one hard and fast rule, there are some guidelines which you can follow that may free up a little space in your file cabinets.As a general rule, the IRS suggests retaining records for 7 years following the year in which expenses are claimed on your tax return. The standard IRS audit only goes back 3 years. However, the IRS has six years to challenge your return if it seems you under reported your gross income by 25% or more. If you file a fraudulent return or no return, you should hold onto any records for 7 years.What about the actual tax returns? The IRS encourages you to keep federal tax returns until the period of limitations expires. This is the time period you have to claim a credit or refund or the time frame they have to levy additional taxes on you. State returns should be saved for the same time period. In most cases, you are safe to toss them after 7 years.If you plan to claim a credit or refund after you file, then you should retain relevant tax records for 3 years. If you claim a loss from worthless securities or bad debt deduction, you should keep related records for 7 years. Employment tax records should be held for 4 years after the date the tax becomes due or paid, whichever is later.For most investments and banking statements, the year-end statement is the most important. If you have any investment liquidations that generated capital gains or losses, you will want to keep the statements related to those transactions. Investment purchase information should be kept at least until the cost basis and purchase date is reflected on your account statements. Those figures will be used in future gain/loss calculations. Real estate documents, including closing statements, mortgage information, and expenses incurred to improve the property should be kept as long as you own the property. Once the property is sold, keep documents showing the deed recording and the mortgage pay-off receipt. It is also advisable to hold onto those receipts for 7 years after you sell, exchange or liquidate any real property.If you make any contributions, receive distributions, or rollover any IRAs or other qualified plans, you’ll need to document those transactions. The IRS wants to make sure they receive any taxes due and will penalize violations. Keep your annual 401(k) statements and any Form 8606 (nondeductible contributions to traditional IRAs), Form 5498 (contribution information), or Form 1099-R (distributions) you receive. While Roth IRAs are funded with after-tax dollars, you need to keep those records until you are 59 ½ and have had the account for at least 5 years.If you anticipate needing to apply for Medicaid, you’ll want to keep fairly complete financial history documentation. Medicaid has a five-year "lookback" period in many states, so to qualify for aid you have to prove that you didn’t transfer any assets except those specifically allowed. Medical records and medical insurance documents should be held onto for about 5 years from when services are rendered. If the medical expenses are claimed on your taxes, however, you’ll want to keep them for 7 years following the year they are claimed.Life insurance policy information should be kept for the life of the policy plus 3 years.Small business owners will likely need to keep any payroll documents for at least 7 years. Should there be a lawsuit or a legal dispute involving your company or one of its employees, a detailed financial history would be helpful.As a reminder, it’s a good idea to shred any documents you’re disposing that have personal information on them (social security numbers, active account numbers, etc.). And while you’re sorting through all your files, who knows – you may uncover some new projects that need attending to, like updating your Powers of Attorney or completing a household inventory for your insurance.If you have any questions, feel free to give us a call at (847-559-0180) or send us an email (info@hochmanandbaker.com).





