Thursday, March 10, 2011










How Long to Keep Those Documents?This is the time of year when we all start thinking about income taxes. As you wade through your piles of receipts and various statements, you may question which documents need to be saved and for how long. Although there is no one hard and fast rule, there are some guidelines which you can follow that may free up a little space in your file cabinets.As a general rule, the IRS suggests retaining records for 7 years following the year in which expenses are claimed on your tax return. The standard IRS audit only goes back 3 years. However, the IRS has six years to challenge your return if it seems you under reported your gross income by 25% or more. For most investments and banking statements, the year-end statement is the most important. If you have any investment liquidations that generated capital gains or losses, you will want to keep the statements related to those transactions. Investment purchase information should be kept at least until the cost basis and purchase date is reflected on your account statements. Those figures will be used in future gain/loss calculations.Real estate documents, including closing statements, mortgage information, and expenses incurred to improve the property should be kept as long as you own the property. Once the property is sold, keep documents showing the deed recording and the mortgage pay-off receipt.If you make any contributions, receive distributions, or rollover any IRAs or other qualified plans, you’ll need to document those transactions. The IRS wants to make sure they receive any taxes due and will penalize violations. If you anticipate needing to apply for Medicaid, you’ll want to keep fairly complete financial history documentation. Medicaid has a five-year "lookback" period in many states, so to qualify for aid you have to prove that you didn’t transfer any assets except those specifically allowed.As a reminder, it’s a good idea to shred any documents you’re disposing that have personal information on them (social security numbers, active account numbers, etc.). And while you’re sorting through all your files, who knows – you may uncover some new projects that need attending to, like updating your Powers of Attorney or completing a household inventory for your insurance.Have any questions? Feel free to give us a call at 847-559-0180 or send us an email at info@hochmanandbaker.com





