Friday, October 29, 2010







IRA Consolidation: Are You Missing Out on a Chance to Make Your Life Simpler?





Are you one of the many Americans who has several retirement accounts? Were some of these rolled over from previous employers and held in a variety of places? Have you had years where you almost forgot about one or two of these accounts?Consider consolidating your current IRA accounts into a single account with your financial adviser. You’ll find that eliminating multiple accounts may reduce fees charged by institutions for holding these IRAs, makes monitoring performance easier, and allows your financial adviser to take a more comprehensive approach to managing your portfolio. In addition, a consolidated account will make matters much clearer when you begin to take your Required Minimum Distributions.Remember to also speak with your financial adviser about any 401(k) plans you may still have with former employers. These can be rolled into your IRA which may provide  many more options for investing. As a self-directed IRA, you will have access to a multitude of investment choices, whereas most company plans offer less than twenty. These additional options allow you to choose how you invest your money based on your individual preferences, i.e. risk level, expense costs, exposure to specific industries, time frames, etc. While company 401(k) plans have strong selling points, such as company matching provisions, when you are no longer working for that company, they vanish. The benefits of IRAs are numerous and are especially favorable to the alternative of keeping a plan with a former employer. Not only can a self-directed IRA be more easily coordinated with your other financial holdings, but your beneficiaries have more flexibility with an IRA. Beneficiaries of IRAs usually have the option to stretch receipt of distributions over their lifetimes (and consequently the corresponding taxes) but most company plans do not allow this option. When stretch IRAs are not allowed, a beneficiary will be required to take a lump sum distribution and pay income tax on the entire amount in that tax year. This can be a tremendous burden and reduces the net inheritance considerably. Also, if you are currently contributing to a 401(k) plan, another option for you to consider is taking an in-service distribution. Although limited by the provisions of the plan, these in-service distributions allow you to roll money from your company’s plan into your self-directed IRA which will provide you with more investment options for that qualified money. It’s common for individuals to have too heavy a weighting of their employer’s stock in the 401(k) plan. While company loyalty is admirable, it is often wise to roll a portion of that holding out of the plan into an IRA and reallocate to reduce risk. It’s worth your time to think about consolidating your IRAs. Talk to your financial adviser and make sure you’ve considered your alternatives.This information is not meant as tax or legal advice. Please consult your financial adviser or a tax professional for more information.Have any questions? Feel free to give us a call (847-559-0180) or send us and email (info@hochmanandbaker.com)





