Tuesday, March 9, 2010







529 College Savings Plans





 Have you heard about the study conducted by the Department Agriculture, Expenditures on Children by Families? They have been tracking the cost of raising a child since 1960 and report that a two-parent, middle-income family can expect to spend $221,190 (they estimate from $11,610 to $13,480 per year for 17 years) to raise a child born in 2008. This figure is not adjusted for inflation, nor does it include any college costs!     With the costs for raising a child so high, a lot of people wonder how they can possibly afford to save money for their child’s education. Even if you can’t save a lot of money, your children or grandchildren can still benefit greatly from a college savings plan. One of the more popular ways to save for college is a 529 college savings plan. These savings plans are managed by investment firms or state government agencies and provide a tax advantaged way to save for higher education.    A 529 savings plan is flexible—you can open a 529 plan for anyone (a child, a grandchild, a friend) and there are no income limits. You can contribute up to $13,000 ($26,000 for married couples) a year without gift tax consequences. Plans are administered by individual states, but investors may choose any plan, regardless of where they live. Also, you can pay for educational expenses at any eligible institution, not just schools in the state of the plan.    The tax advantages are the major draw for 529 plans. The main tax advantages are that the principal grows tax-deferred and the distributions for qualified educational expenses are exempt from tax. Qualified educational expenses include tuition, fees, book, supplies, and equipment required for study at any accredited college, university, or vocational school. (The money can be used for room and board as long as the beneficiary is at least a half-time student.) If a distribution from a 529 plan is not used for a qualified education expenses, then it is subject to income tax and possibly a 10% early distribution penalty. Though contributions are not deductible for federal income tax purposes, many states provide state income tax deductions.     To find out more about saving for college, check out this website that has tools for calculating college costs and more information on 529 and other college savings plans: http://www.savingforcollege.com/    To see the study Expenditures on Children by Families by the Department of Agriculture, visit:  http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/Publications/CRC/crc2008.pdf    This information is not meant as tax or legal advice. Please consult your financial advisor for more information.  Have any questions? Feel free to give us a call (847-559-0180) or send us an email (info@hochmanandbaker.com).





