Friday, February 12, 2010







Roth IRA Conversions in 2010





What’s New for 2010Starting in 2010, the $100,000 modified AGI (Adjusted Gross Income) limit for conversions to Roth IRAs is eliminated. Also, married taxpayers filing separate returns can now convert amounts into a Roth IRA. For conversions in 2010, any amounts required to be included in income are included in income in equal amounts in 2011 and 2012. You can elect to include the entire amount in income in 2010.Benefits of ConversionThe main difference between traditional IRA and Roth IRAs is the way in which the contributions and distributions are taxed. Contributions to traditional IRAs are tax deductible; however you must pay taxes on the distributions. Contributions to Roth IRAs are made on an after-tax basis and, consequently, you do not have to pay taxes on that money again. Distributions are tax free after age 59 ½ (as long as you have had the Roth IRA for five years). This is an attractive option for young investors as they will mostly likely be in a higher tax bracket in retirement than they are now. However, Roth IRAs are not just for the young! Older investors can benefit from conversion to a Roth, especially if they do not have an immediate need for their IRA assets. If you name your spouse as the beneficiary of your Roth IRA, your spouse can treat his/her inherited IRA as their own and he/she will not be required to take withdrawals. This provides an opportunity for further compounding for the rest of your spouse’s life. Then, your spouse’s beneficiary, a child or grandchild for example, and he/she can then take withdrawals according to their life expectancy. All the while, the assets continue to compound tax free!Note: If you made after-tax contributions to your traditional IRA, then that portion of the total contributions can be distributed tax-free. In the case of a conversion, the tax on the IRA assets would be solely on the portion of the before-tax contributions.Conversion DrawbacksA conversion from a traditional to a Roth IRA is a taxable event. You can pay taxes on the conversion amount out of the IRA or with outside funds. However, if you are under 59 ½ paying the tax from the IRA would result in a 10% penalty. The good news, as mentioned above, is that you can divide the taxes between your 2011 and 2012 tax returns. Consult Your Financial AdvisorBefore you arrange for any rollover or conversion, it is a good idea to consult a financial advisor. Each person’s financial circumstances are different and any tax consequences should be fully understood before any action is taken. This information is not meant as tax or legal advice. Please consult your financial advisor for more information.Have any questions? Feel free to give us a call (847-559-0180) or send us an email (info@hochmanandbaker.com).





